'''Phanto''' (or '''Phanton''', {{lang-el|Φάντων}}; 4th century BC) of [[Phlius]], was a [[Pythagoreanism|Pythagorean]] philosopher, and one of the last of the school until the [[Neopythagorean]] revival in the Roman era. He was a disciple of [[Philolaus]] and [[Eurytus (Pythagorean)|Eurytus]], and, probably in his old age, contemporary with [[Aristoxenus]], the [[Peripatetic school|Peripatetic]] philosopher, c. 320 BC.<ref>Iamblichus, ''de Vit. Pythag.'' cc. 35, 36.</ref><ref>Diogenes Laërtius, viii. 46</ref>
